# The combination of xs, asm, orc, jit, threads, and kms represents a
# performance-oriented configuration that maximizes hardware utilization and
# system responsiveness. The asm, orc, and jit flags empower software to use
# hand-optimized assembly routines and just-in-time compilation, which
# significantly accelerates tasks like media processing and script execution. By
# including threads and kms, you ensure the system is optimized for multi-core
# parallelism and flicker-free, high-resolution graphics output via the kernel's
# display manager.
*/* xs asm orc jit threads kms

# Unlike the standard glibc malloc, jemalloc significantly reduces memory
# fragmentation and lock contention in heavily multithreaded applications and
# long-running daemons like tmux. Applying this flag universally ensures that
# any software explicitly validated by Gentoo maintainers to support jemalloc
# will use it for better memory efficiency, while safely defaulting to glibc for
# unsupported applications like Emacs to maintain system stability.
*/* jemalloc

# The GNU Multiple Precision Arithmetic Library (dev-libs/gmp) is extensively
# optimized for arbitrary-precision arithmetic.
*/* gmp

# native-extensions: This flag influences how certain interpreted language
# packages compile performance-sensitive subroutines into native binary code.
*/* native-extensions

# Enable Link Time Optimization (LTO) and Profile-Guided Optimization (PGO).
#
# LTO allows the compiler to perform whole-program optimizations during linking,
# while PGO uses runtime profiling data to guide optimizations during a
# subsequent build. These optimizations can improve performance and reduce
# binary size, but they also increase build time, memory usage, and may expose
# package-specific build issues.
sys-devel/gcc lto pgo

dev-lang/rust lto

app-arch/xz-utils pgo
app-shells/bash pgo
dev-lang/python pgo
media-libs/svt-av1 pgo
sys-devel/binutils pgo

# mold: Link against mimalloc (Microsoft Research's mimalloc allocator).
#
# Benefits:
# - Maximizes multi-threaded linking speed by replacing standard glibc malloc.
#   Since mold is designed to process object files in parallel across all CPU
#   cores, standard global allocation locks create a severe performance
#   bottleneck. mimalloc uses thread-local heaps to eliminate this contention.
# - Improves CPU cache locality by grouping allocations strictly by size class
#   inside distinct memory pages, speeding up symbol resolution passes.
# - Minimizes internal memory fragmentation during rapid, short-lived allocation
#   cycles characteristic of large toolchain link phases.
#
# Drawbacks:
# - Results in a larger virtual memory footprint (VSIZE) because mimalloc
#   pre-allocates broad virtual address regions from the Linux kernel upfront.
# - Yields diminishing returns on processors with low core counts or thread-
#   constrained configurations where allocator contention is not a major factor.
# - Offers fewer native diagnostics and profiling hooks compared to jemalloc,
#   reducing visibility during deep toolchain troubleshooting.
sys-devel/mold mimalloc

# Spidermonkey is the core JavaScript engine driving the GNOME desktop
# environment shell via GJS. Upstream Mozilla developers optimize this engine
# heavily for the LLVM ecosystem. Compiling it with Clang rather than GCC
# provides faster execution layouts, resulting in snappier window animations and
# UI responses.
dev-lang/spidermonkey clang

